# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: momentum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] The **Abraham–Minkowski controversy** is a physics debate concerning electromagnetic momentum within dielectric media.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] Two equations were first suggested by Hermann Minkowski (1908) and Max Abraham (1909) for this momentum.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] They predict different values, from which the name of the controversy derives.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] Experimental support has been claimed for both.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] The two points of view have different physical interpretations and thus neither need be more correct than the other.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] Griffiths argues that, in the presence of matter, only the total stress–energy tensor carries unambiguous physical significance; how one apportions it between an "electromagnetic" part and a "matter" part depends on context and convenience.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] Several papers have claimed to have resolved this controversy.
[src:momentum/abraham-minkowski-controversy] The controversy is still claimed to have importance in physics beyond the Standard Model where electrodynamics gets modifications, like in the presence of axions.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] A version of the concept of absolute space (in the sense of a preferred frame) can be seen in Aristotelian physics.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Westman writes that a "whiff" of absolute space can be observed in Copernicus's *De revolutionibus orbium coelestium*, where Copernicus uses the concept of an immobile sphere of stars.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Originally introduced by Sir Isaac Newton in *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, the concepts of absolute time and space provided a theoretical foundation that facilitated Newtonian mechanics.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] According to Newton, absolute time exists independently of any perceiver and progresses at a consistent pace throughout the universe.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Unlike relative time, Newton believed absolute time was imperceptible and could only be understood mathematically.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] According to Newton, humans are only capable of perceiving relative time, which is a measurement of perceivable objects in motion (like the Moon or Sun).
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] From these movements, we infer the passage of time.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] These notions imply that absolute space and time do not depend upon physical events, but are a backdrop or stage setting within which physical phenomena occur.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Thus, every object has an absolute state of motion relative to absolute space, so that an object must be either in a state of absolute rest, or moving at some absolute speed.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Historically, there have been differing views on the concept of absolute space and time.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Gottfried Leibniz was of the opinion that space made no sense except as the relative location of bodies, and time made no sense except as the relative movement of bodies.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] A more recent form of these objections was made by Ernst Mach.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Mach's principle proposes that mechanics is entirely about relative motion of bodies and, in particular, mass is an expression of such relative motion.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] So, for example, a single particle in a universe with no other bodies would have zero mass.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] According to Mach, Newton's examples simply illustrate relative rotation of spheres and the bulk of the universe.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] These views opposing absolute space and time may be seen from a modern stance as an attempt to introduce operational definitions for space and time, a perspective made explicit in the special theory of relativity.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Even within the context of Newtonian mechanics, the modern view is that absolute space is unnecessary.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Instead, the notion of inertial frame of reference has taken precedence, that is, a preferred *set* of frames of reference that move uniformly with respect to one another.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Newton himself recognized the role of inertial frames.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] As a practical matter, inertial frames often are taken as frames moving uniformly with respect to the fixed stars.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] See Inertial frame of reference for more discussion on this.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] I do not define time, space, place and motion, as being well known to all.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] The concepts of space and time were separate in physical theory prior to the advent of special relativity theory, which connected the two and showed both to be dependent upon the reference frame's motion.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] In Einstein's theories, the ideas of absolute time and space were superseded by the notion of spacetime in special relativity, and curved spacetime in general relativity.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Quoted below from his later papers, Einstein identified the term aether with "properties of space", a terminology that is not widely used.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Einstein stated that in general relativity the "aether" is not absolute anymore, as the geodesic and therefore the structure of spacetime depends on the presence of matter.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] Special relativity eliminates absolute time (although Gödel and others suspect absolute time may be valid for some forms of general relativity) and general relativity further reduces the physical scope of absolute space and time through the concept of geodesics.
[src:momentum/absolute-time-and-space] There appears to be absolute space in relation to the distant stars because the local geodesics eventually channel information from these stars, but it is not necessary to invoke absolute space with respect to any system's physics, as its local geodesics are sufficient to describe its spacetime.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:momentum/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:momentum/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:momentum/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:momentum/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:momentum/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:momentum/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:momentum/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:momentum/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:momentum/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:momentum/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:momentum/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:momentum/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:momentum/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:momentum/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:momentum/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:momentum/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:momentum/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:momentum/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:momentum/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:momentum/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:momentum/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:momentum/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:momentum/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:momentum/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:momentum/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:momentum/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:momentum/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:momentum/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:momentum/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:momentum/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:momentum/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:momentum/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] In astrophysics, **accretion** is the accumulation of particles into a massive object by gravitationally attracting more matter, typically gaseous matter, into an accretion disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Most astronomical objects, such as galaxies, stars, and planets, are formed by accretion processes.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion model that Earth and the other terrestrial planets formed from meteoric material was proposed in 1944 by Otto Schmidt, followed by the *protoplanet theory* of William McCrea (1960) and finally the *capture theory* of Michael Woolfson.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] In 1978, Andrew Prentice resurrected the initial Laplacian ideas about planet formation and developed the *modern Laplacian theory*.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] None of these models proved completely successful, and many of the proposed theories were descriptive.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The 1944 accretion model by Otto Schmidt was further developed in a quantitative way in 1969 by Viktor Safronov.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] He calculated, in detail, the different stages of terrestrial planet formation.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Since then, the model has been further developed using intensive numerical simulations to study planetesimal accumulation.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] It is now accepted that stars form by the gravitational collapse of interstellar gas.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Prior to collapse, this gas is mostly in the form of molecular clouds, such as the Orion Nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As the cloud collapses, losing potential energy, it heats up, gaining kinetic energy, and the conservation of angular momentum ensures that the cloud forms a flattened disk—the accretion disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] A few hundred thousand years after the Big Bang, the Universe cooled to the point where atoms could form.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As the Universe continued to expand and cool, the atoms lost enough kinetic energy, and dark matter coalesced sufficiently, to form protogalaxies.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As further accretion occurred, galaxies formed.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Galaxies grow through mergers and smooth gas accretion.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion also occurs inside galaxies, forming stars.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Stars are thought to form inside giant clouds of cold molecular hydrogen — giant molecular clouds of roughly 300,000 *M*☉ and 65 light-years (20 pc) in diameter.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Over millions of years, giant molecular clouds are prone to collapse and fragmentation.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] These fragments then form small, dense cores, which in turn collapse into stars.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The cores range in mass from a fraction to several times that of the Sun and are called protostellar (protosolar) nebulae.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Compare it with the particle number density of the air at the sea level — 2.8×1019/cm3 (4.6×1020/cu in).
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The initial collapse of a solar-mass protostellar nebula takes around 100,000 years.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Every nebula begins with a certain amount of angular momentum.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Gas in the central part of the nebula, with relatively low angular momentum, undergoes fast compression and forms a hot hydrostatic (non-contracting) core containing a small fraction of the mass of the original nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] This core forms the seed of what will become a star.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As the collapse continues, conservation of angular momentum dictates that the rotation of the infalling envelope accelerates, which eventually forms a disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As the infall of material from the disk continues, the envelope eventually becomes thin and transparent and the young stellar object (YSO) becomes observable, initially in far-infrared light and later in the visible.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Around this time the protostar begins to fuse deuterium.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] If the protostar is sufficiently massive (above 80 *M*J), hydrogen fusion follows.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Otherwise, if its mass is too low, the object becomes a brown dwarf.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] This birth of a new star occurs approximately 100,000 years after the collapse begins.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Objects at this stage are known as Class I protostars, which are also called young T Tauri stars, evolved protostars, or young stellar objects.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] By this time, the forming star has already accreted much of its mass; the total mass of the disk and remaining envelope does not exceed 10–20% of the mass of the central YSO.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] At the next stage, the envelope completely disappears, having been gathered up by the disk, and the protostar becomes a classical T Tauri star.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The latter have accretion disks and continue to accrete hot gas, which manifests itself by strong emission lines in their spectrum.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The former do not possess accretion disks.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Classical T Tauri stars evolve into weakly lined T Tauri stars.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] This happens after about 1 million years.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The mass of the disk around a classical T Tauri star is about 1–3% of the stellar mass, and it is accreted at a rate of 10−7 to 10−9 *M*☉ per year.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] A pair of bipolar jets is usually present as well.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The accretion explains all peculiar properties of classical T Tauri stars: strong flux in the emission lines (up to 100% of the intrinsic luminosity of the star), magnetic activity, photometric variability and jets.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The emission lines actually form as the accreted gas hits the "surface" of the star, which happens around its magnetic poles.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The jets are byproducts of accretion: they carry away excessive angular momentum.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The classical T Tauri stage lasts about 10 million years (there are only a few examples of so-called Peter Pan disks, where the accretion continues to persist for much longer periods, sometimes lasting for more than 40 million years).
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The disk eventually disappears due to accretion onto the central star, planet formation, ejection by jets, and photoevaporation by ultraviolet radiation from the central star and nearby stars.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] As a result, the young star becomes a weakly lined T Tauri star, which, over hundreds of millions of years, evolves into an ordinary Sun-like star, dependent on its initial mass.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Self-accretion of cosmic dust accelerates the growth of the particles into boulder-sized planetesimals.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The more massive planetesimals accrete some smaller ones, while others shatter in collisions.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Accretion disks are common around smaller stars, stellar remnants in a close binary, or black holes surrounded by material (such as those at the centers of galaxies).
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Some dynamics in the disk, such as dynamical friction, are necessary to allow orbiting gas to lose angular momentum and fall onto the central massive object.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Occasionally, this can result in stellar surface fusion (see Bondi accretion).
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] In the formation of terrestrial planets or planetary cores, several stages can be considered.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] First, when gas and dust grains collide, they agglomerate by microphysical processes like van der Waals forces and electromagnetic forces, forming micrometer-sized particles.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] During this stage, accumulation mechanisms are largely non-gravitational in nature.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] However, planetesimal formation in the centimeter-to-meter range is not well understood, and no convincing explanation is offered as to why such grains would accumulate rather than simply rebound.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Ward (1996) suggests that when slow moving grains collide, the very low, yet non-zero, gravity of colliding grains impedes their escape.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] It is also thought that grain fragmentation plays an important role replenishing small grains and keeping the disk thick, but also in maintaining a relatively high abundance of solids of all sizes.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] A number of mechanisms have been proposed for crossing the 'meter-sized' barrier.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Local concentrations of pebbles may form, which then gravitationally collapse into planetesimals the size of large asteroids.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] These concentrations can occur passively due to the structure of the gas disk, for example, between eddies, at pressure bumps, at the edge of a gap created by a giant planet, or at the boundaries of turbulent regions of the disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Or, the particles may take an active role in their concentration via a feedback mechanism referred to as a streaming instability.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] In a streaming instability the interaction between the solids and the gas in the protoplanetary disk results in the growth of local concentrations, as new particles accumulate in the wake of small concentrations, causing them to grow into massive filaments.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Alternatively, if the grains that form due to the agglomeration of dust are highly porous their growth may continue until they become large enough to collapse due to their own gravity.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The low density of these objects allows them to remain strongly coupled with the gas, thereby avoiding high velocity collisions which could result in their erosion or fragmentation.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Grains eventually stick together to form mountain-size (or larger) bodies called planetesimals.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Collisions and gravitational interactions between planetesimals combine to produce Moon-size planetary embryos (protoplanets) over roughly 0.1–1 million years.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Finally, the planetary embryos collide to form planets over 10–100 million years.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The planetesimals are massive enough that mutual gravitational interactions are significant enough to be taken into account when computing their evolution.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Growth is aided by orbital decay of smaller bodies due to gas drag, which prevents them from being stranded between orbits of the embryos.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Further collisions and accumulation lead to terrestrial planets or the core of giant planets.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] If the planetesimals formed via the gravitational collapse of local concentrations of pebbles, their growth into planetary embryos and the cores of giant planets is dominated by the further accretions of pebbles.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion is aided by the gas drag felt by objects as they accelerate toward a massive body.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Gas drag slows the pebbles below the escape velocity of the massive body causing them to spiral toward and to be accreted by it.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Pebble accretion may accelerate the formation of planets by a factor of 1000 compared to the accretion of planetesimals, allowing giant planets to form before the dissipation of the gas disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] However, core growth via pebble accretion appears incompatible with the final masses and compositions of Uranus and Neptune.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Direct calculations indicate that, in a typical protoplanetary disk, the formation time of a giant planet via pebble accretion is comparable to the formation times resulting from planetesimal accretion.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The formation of terrestrial planets differs from that of giant gas planets, also called Jovian planets.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The particles that make up the terrestrial planets are made from metal and rock that condensed in the inner Solar System.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] However, Jovian planets began as large, icy planetesimals, which then captured hydrogen and helium gas from the solar nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Differentiation between these two classes of planetesimals arises due to the frost line of the solar nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Meteorites contain a record of accretion and impacts during all stages of asteroid origin and evolution; however, the mechanism of asteroid accretion and growth is not well understood.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Evidence suggests the main growth of asteroids can result from gas-assisted accretion of chondrules, which are millimeter-sized spherules that form as molten (or partially molten) droplets in space before being accreted to their parent asteroids.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] In the inner Solar System, chondrules appear to have been crucial for initiating accretion.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The tiny mass of asteroids may be partly due to inefficient chondrule formation beyond 2 AU, or less-efficient delivery of chondrules from near the protostar.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Also, impacts controlled the formation and destruction of asteroids, and are thought to be a major factor in their geological evolution.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Chondrules, metal grains, and other components likely formed in the solar nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] These accreted together to form parent asteroids.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Some of these bodies subsequently melted, forming metallic cores and olivine-rich mantles; others were aqueously altered.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] After the asteroids had cooled, they were eroded by impacts for 4.5 billion years, or disrupted.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] For accretion to occur, impact velocities must be less than about twice the escape velocity, which is about 140 m/s (460 ft/s) for a 100 km (60 mi) radius asteroid.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Simple models for accretion in the asteroid belt generally assume micrometer-sized dust grains sticking together and settling to the midplane of the nebula to form a dense layer of dust, which, because of gravitational forces, was converted into a disk of kilometer-sized planetesimals.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] But, several arguments suggest that asteroids may not have accreted this way.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Comets, or their precursors, formed in the outer Solar System, possibly millions of years before planet formation.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] How and when comets formed is debated, with distinct implications for Solar System formation, dynamics, and geology.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Three-dimensional computer simulations indicate the major structural features observed on cometary nuclei can be explained by pairwise low velocity accretion of weak cometesimals.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The currently favored formation mechanism is that of the nebular hypothesis, which states that comets are probably a remnant of the original planetesimal "building blocks" from which the planets grew.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Astronomers think that comets originate in both the Oort cloud and the scattered disk.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Because the scattered disk is dynamically active and the Kuiper belt relatively dynamically stable, the scattered disk is now seen as the most likely point of origin for periodic comets.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The classic Oort cloud theory states that the Oort cloud, a sphere measuring about 50,000 AU (0.24 pc) in radius, formed at the same time as the solar nebula and occasionally releases comets into the inner Solar System as a giant planet or star passes nearby and causes gravitational disruptions.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Examples of such comet clouds may already have been seen in the Helix Nebula.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] The *Rosetta* mission to comet 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko determined in 2015 that when Sun's heat penetrates the surface, it triggers evaporation (sublimation) of buried ice.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] While some of the resulting water vapour may escape from the nucleus, 80% of it recondenses in layers beneath the surface.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] This observation implies that the thin ice-rich layers exposed close to the surface may be a consequence of cometary activity and evolution, and that global layering does not necessarily occur early in the comet's formation history.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] While most scientists thought that all the evidence indicated that the structure of nuclei of comets is processed rubble piles of smaller ice planetesimals of a previous generation, the *Rosetta* mission confirmed the idea that comets are "rubble piles" of disparate material.
[src:momentum/accretion-astrophysics] Comets appear to have formed as ~100-km bodies, then overwhelmingly ground/recontacted into their present states.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] We can have these equations work for a moving medium by setting $\mathbf {w} =\mathbf {u} +\mathbf {v}$ , where $\mathbf {u}$ is the constant velocity that the whole fluid is moving at before being disturbed (equivalent to a moving observer) and $\mathbf {v}$ is the fluid velocity.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Note that setting $\mathbf {u} =0$ returns the equations at rest.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Let us now take $\mathbf {v} ,\rho ',p'$ to all be small quantities.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] In the case that we keep terms to first order, for the continuity equation, we have the $\rho '\mathbf {v}$ term going to 0.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] This similarly applies for the density perturbation times the time derivative of the velocity.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Moreover, the spatial components of the material derivative go to 0.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Thus the velocity potential $\phi$ obeys the wave equation in the limit of small disturbances.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] The boundary conditions required to solve for the potential come from the fact that the velocity of the fluid must be 0 normal to the fixed surfaces of the system.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Thus, the velocity potential, pressure, and density all obey the wave equation.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Moreover, we only need to solve one such equation to determine all other three.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Again, we can derive the small-disturbance limit for sound waves in a moving medium.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] This differential equation must be solved with the appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:momentum/acoustic-theory] Note that setting $\mathbf {u} =0$ returns us the wave equation.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] In physics, the **acoustic wave equation** is a second-order partial differential equation that governs the propagation of acoustic waves through a material medium resp. a standing wavefield.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] The equation describes the evolution of acoustic pressure p or particle velocity **u** as a function of position **x** and time t.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] A simplified (scalar) form of the equation describes acoustic waves in only one spatial dimension, while a more general form describes waves in three dimensions.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] For lossy media, more intricate models need to be applied in order to take into account frequency-dependent attenuation and phase speed.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] Such models include acoustic wave equations that incorporate fractional derivative terms, see also the acoustic attenuation article or the survey paper.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] where p is the acoustic pressure (the local deviation from the ambient pressure) and c the speed of sound, using subscript notation for the partial derivatives.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] where T the absolute temperature of the gas and specific gas constant $R_{\text{specific}}$ .
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] Then, assuming the process is adiabatic, pressure $P(\rho )$ can be considered a function of density $\rho$ .
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] To linearize this equation, let $q(x,t)=q_{0}+{\tilde {q}}(x,t),$ where $q_{0}=(\rho _{0},\rho _{0}u_{0})$ is the (constant) background state and ${\tilde {q}}$ is a sufficiently small perturbation, i.e., any powers or products of ${\tilde {q}}$ can be discarded.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] where f and g are any two twice-differentiable functions.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] This may be pictured as the superposition of two waveforms of arbitrary profile, one ( f ) traveling up the x-axis and the other ( g ) down the x-axis at the speed c .
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency of the wave and k is its wave number.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] where $\nabla ^{2}$ is the Laplace operator, p is the acoustic pressure (the local deviation from the ambient pressure), and c is the speed of sound.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] The following solutions are obtained by separation of variables in different coordinate systems.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] They are phasor solutions, that is they have an implicit time-dependence factor of $e^{i\omega t}$ where $\omega =2\pi f$ is the angular frequency.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] Depending on the chosen Fourier convention, one of these represents an outward travelling wave and the other a nonphysical inward travelling wave.
[src:momentum/acoustic-wave-equation] The inward travelling solution wave is only nonphysical because of the singularity that occurs at r=0; inward travelling waves do exist.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Hearing is one of the most crucial means of survival in the animal world and speech is one of the most distinctive characteristics of human development and culture.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Accordingly, the science of acoustics spreads across many facets of human society—music, medicine, architecture, industrial production, warfare and more.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Likewise, animal species such as songbirds and frogs use sound and hearing as a key element of mating rituals or for marking territories.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Art, craft, science and technology have provoked one another to advance the whole, as in many other fields of knowledge.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Robert Bruce Lindsay's "Wheel of Acoustics" is a well-accepted overview of the various fields in acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The word "acoustic" is derived from the ἀκουστικός (*akoustikós*), meaning "of or for hearing" and "ready to hear", and from ἀκουστός (*akoustós*), "heard, audible", which in turn derives from the verb ἀκούω (*akoúō*), "to hear".
[src:momentum/acoustics] The Latin synonym is "sonic", after which the term **sonics** used to be a synonym for acoustics and later a branch of acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Frequencies above and below the audible range are called "ultrasonic" and "infrasonic", respectively.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In the 6th century BCE, the ancient Greek philosopher Pythagoras wanted to know why some combinations of musical sounds seemed more beautiful than others, and he found answers in terms of numerical ratios representing the harmonic overtone series on a string.
[src:momentum/acoustics] He is reputed to have observed that when the lengths of vibrating strings are expressible as ratios of integers (e.g.
[src:momentum/acoustics] 2 to 3, 3 to 4), the tones produced will be harmonious, and the smaller the integers the more harmonious the sounds.
[src:momentum/acoustics] For example, a string of a certain length would sound particularly harmonious with a string of twice the length (other factors being equal).
[src:momentum/acoustics] In modern parlance, if a string sounds the note C when plucked, a string twice as long will sound a C an octave lower.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In one system of musical tuning, the tones in between are then given by 16:9 for D, 8:5 for E, 3:2 for F, 4:3 for G, 6:5 for A, and 16:15 for B, in ascending order.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) understood that sound consisted of compressions and rarefactions of air which "falls upon and strikes the air which is next to it...", a very good expression of the nature of wave motion.
[src:momentum/acoustics] *On Things Heard*, generally ascribed to Strato of Lampsacus, states that the pitch is related to the frequency of vibrations of the air and to the speed of sound.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In about 20 BCE, the Roman architect and engineer Vitruvius wrote a treatise on the acoustic properties of theaters, including a discussion of interference, echoes, and reverberation—the beginnings of architectural acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In Book V of his *De architectura* (*The Ten Books of Architecture*) Vitruvius described sound as a wave comparable to a water wave extended to three dimensions, which, when interrupted by obstructions, would flow back and break up following waves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] During the Islamic golden age, Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) is believed to have postulated that the speed of sound was much slower than the speed of light.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The physical understanding of acoustical processes advanced rapidly during and after the Scientific Revolution.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Mainly Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) but also Marin Mersenne (1588–1648), independently, discovered the complete laws of vibrating strings (completing what Pythagoras and Pythagoreans had started 2000 years earlier).
[src:momentum/acoustics] Galileo wrote "Waves are produced by the vibrations of a sonorous body, which spread through the air, bringing to the tympanum of the ear a stimulus which the mind interprets as sound", a remarkable statement that points to the beginnings of physiological and psychological acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Experimental measurements of the speed of sound in air were carried out successfully between 1630 and 1680 by a number of investigators, prominently Mersenne.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Inspired by Mersenne's *Harmonie universelle* (*Universal Harmony*) of 1634, the Rome-based Jesuit scholar Athanasius Kircher undertook research in acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Kircher published two major books on acoustics: the *Musurgia universalis* (*Universal Music-Making*) in 1650 and the *Phonurgia nova* (*New Sound-Making*) in 1673.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Meanwhile, Newton (1642–1727) derived the relationship for wave velocity in solids, a cornerstone of physical acoustics (Principia, 1687).
[src:momentum/acoustics] Substantial progress in acoustics, resting on firmer mathematical and physical concepts, was made during the eighteenth century by Euler (1707–1783), Lagrange (1736–1813), and d'Alembert (1717–1783).
[src:momentum/acoustics] During this era, continuum physics, or field theory, began to receive a definite mathematical structure.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The wave equation emerged in a number of contexts, including the propagation of sound in air.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Also in the 19th century, Wheatstone, Ohm, and Henry developed the analogy between electricity and acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The twentieth century saw a burgeoning of technological applications of the large body of scientific knowledge that was by then in place.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The first such application was Sabine's groundbreaking work in architectural acoustics, and many others followed.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Underwater acoustics was used for detecting submarines in the First World War.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Sound recording and the telephone played important roles in a global transformation of society.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Sound measurement and analysis reached new levels of accuracy and sophistication through the use of electronics and computing.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The ultrasonic frequency range enabled wholly new kinds of application in medicine and industry.
[src:momentum/acoustics] New kinds of transducers (generators and receivers of acoustic energy) were invented and put to use.
[src:momentum/acoustics] , both suspended on an overhead steel trellis, to synthesize an indoor acoustic environment outdoors.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Acoustics is defined by ANSI/ASA S1.1-2013 as "(a) Science of sound, including its production, transmission, and effects, including biological and psychological effects.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The study of acoustics revolves around the generation, propagation and reception of mechanical waves and vibrations.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The steps shown in the above diagram can be found in any acoustical event or process.
[src:momentum/acoustics] There are many kinds of causes, both natural and volitional.
[src:momentum/acoustics] There are many kinds of transduction processes that convert energy from some other form into sonic energy, producing a sound wave.
[src:momentum/acoustics] There is one fundamental equation that describes sound wave propagation, the acoustic wave equation, but the phenomena that emerge from it are varied and often complex.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The wave carries energy throughout the propagating medium.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Eventually this energy is transduced again into other forms, in ways that again may be natural and/or volitionally contrived.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The final effect may be purely physical or it may reach far into the biological or volitional domains.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The five basic steps are found equally well whether we are talking about an earthquake, a submarine using sonar to locate its foe, or a band playing in a rock concert.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The central stage in the acoustical process is wave propagation.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This falls within the domain of physical acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In fluids, sound propagates primarily as a pressure wave.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In solids, mechanical waves can take many forms including longitudinal waves, transverse waves and surface waves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Acoustics looks first at the pressure levels and frequencies in the sound wave and how the wave interacts with the environment.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This interaction can be described as either a diffraction, interference or a reflection or a mix of the three.
[src:momentum/acoustics] If several media are present, a refraction can also occur.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Transduction processes are also of special importance to acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In fluids such as air and water, sound waves propagate as disturbances in the ambient pressure level.
[src:momentum/acoustics] While this disturbance is usually small, it is still noticeable to the human ear.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The smallest sound that a person can hear, known as the threshold of hearing, is nine orders of magnitude smaller than the ambient pressure.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The loudness of these disturbances is related to the sound pressure level (SPL), which is measured on a logarithmic scale in decibels.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Physicists and acoustic engineers tend to discuss sound pressure levels in terms of frequencies, partly because this is how our ears interpret sound.
[src:momentum/acoustics] What we experience as "higher pitched" or "lower pitched" sounds are pressure vibrations having a higher or lower number of cycles per second.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In a common technique of acoustic measurement, acoustic signals are sampled in time, and then presented in more meaningful forms such as octave bands or time frequency plots.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Both of these popular methods are used to analyze sound and better understand the acoustic phenomenon.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The entire spectrum can be divided into three sections: audio, ultrasonic, and infrasonic.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The audio range falls between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This range is important because its frequencies can be detected by the human ear.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This range has a number of applications, including speech communication and music.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The ultrasonic range refers to the very high frequencies: 20,000 Hz and higher.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This range has shorter wavelengths which allow better resolution in imaging technologies.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Medical applications such as ultrasonography and elastography rely on the ultrasonic frequency range.
[src:momentum/acoustics] On the other end of the spectrum, the lowest frequencies are known as the infrasonic range.
[src:momentum/acoustics] These frequencies can be used to study geological phenomena such as earthquakes.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Analytic instruments such as the spectrum analyzer facilitate visualization and measurement of acoustic signals and their properties.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The spectrogram produced by such an instrument is a graphical display of the time varying pressure level and frequency profiles that give a specific acoustic signal its defining character.
[src:momentum/acoustics] A transducer is a device for converting one form of energy into another.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In an electroacoustic context, this means converting sound energy into electrical energy (or vice versa).
[src:momentum/acoustics] Electroacoustic transducers include loudspeakers, microphones, particle velocity sensors, hydrophones and sonar projectors.
[src:momentum/acoustics] These devices convert a sound wave to or from an electric signal.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The most widely used transduction principles are electromagnetism, electrostatics and piezoelectricity.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The transducers in most common loudspeakers (e.g. woofers and tweeters), are electromagnetic devices that generate waves using a suspended diaphragm driven by an electromagnetic voice coil, sending off pressure waves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Electret microphones and condenser microphones employ electrostatics—as the sound wave strikes the microphone's diaphragm, it moves and induces a voltage change.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The ultrasonic systems used in medical ultrasonography employ piezoelectric transducers.
[src:momentum/acoustics] These are made from special ceramics in which mechanical vibrations and electrical fields are interlinked through a property of the material itself.
[src:momentum/acoustics] An acoustician is an expert in the science of sound.
[src:momentum/acoustics] There are many types of acousticians, but they usually have a Bachelor's degree or higher qualification.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Some possess a degree in acoustics, while others enter the discipline via studies in fields such as physics or engineering.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Much work in acoustics requires a good grounding in mathematics and science.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Many acoustic scientists work in research and development.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Some conduct basic research to advance our knowledge of the perception (e.g. hearing, psychoacoustics or neurophysiology) of speech, music and noise.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Other acoustic scientists advance understanding of how sound is affected as it moves through environments, e.g. underwater acoustics, architectural acoustics or structural acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Other areas of work are listed under subdisciplines below.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Acoustic scientists work in government, university and private industry laboratories.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Many go on to work in acoustical engineering.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Some positions, such as faculty (academic staff) require a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics, also known as the archaeology of sound, is one of the only ways to experience the past with senses other than our eyes.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics is studied by testing the acoustic properties of prehistoric sites, including caves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Iegor Rezkinoff, a sound archaeologist, studies the acoustic properties of caves through natural sounds like humming and whistling.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Archaeological theories of acoustics are focused around ritualistic purposes as well as a way of echolocation in the caves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In archaeology, acoustic sounds and rituals directly correlate as specific sounds were meant to bring ritual participants closer to a spiritual awakening.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Parallels can also be drawn between cave wall paintings and the acoustic properties of the cave; they are both dynamic.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Because archaeoacoustics is a fairly new archaeological subject, acoustic sound is still being tested in these prehistoric sites today.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is the study of noise generated by air movement, for instance via turbulence, and the movement of sound through the fluid air.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This knowledge was applied in the 1920s and '30s to detect aircraft before radar was invented and is applied in acoustical engineering to study how to quieten aircraft.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is important for understanding how wind musical instruments work.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Acoustic signal processing is the electronic manipulation of acoustic signals.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Applications include: active noise control; design for hearing aids or cochlear implants; echo cancellation; music information retrieval, and perceptual coding (e.g.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Architectural acoustics (also known as building acoustics) involves the scientific understanding of how to achieve good sound within a building.
[src:momentum/acoustics] It typically involves the study of speech intelligibility, speech privacy, music quality, and vibration reduction in the built environment.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Commonly studied environments are hospitals, classrooms, dwellings, performance venues, recording and broadcasting studios.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Focus considerations include room acoustics, airborne and impact transmission in building structures, airborne and structure-borne noise control, noise control of building systems and electroacoustic systems.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Bioacoustics is the scientific study of the hearing and calls of animals, as well as how animals are affected by the acoustic and sounds of their habitat.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This subdiscipline is concerned with the recording, manipulation and reproduction of audio using electronics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This might include products such as mobile phones, large scale public address systems or virtual reality systems in research laboratories.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Environmental acoustics is the study of noise and vibrations, and their impact on structures, objects, humans, and animals.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The main aim of these studies is to reduce levels of environmental noise and vibration.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Typical work and research within environmental acoustics concerns the development of models used in simulations, measurement techniques, noise mitigation strategies, and the development of standards and regulations.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Research work now also has a focus on the positive use of sound in urban environments: soundscapes and tranquility.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Examples of noise and vibration sources include railways, road traffic, aircraft, industrial equipment and recreational activities.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Musical acoustics is the study of the physics of acoustic instruments; the audio signal processing used in electronic music; the computer analysis of music and composition, and the perception and cognitive neuroscience of music.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Many studies have been conducted to identify the relationship between acoustics and cognition, or more commonly known as psychoacoustics, in which what one hears is a combination of perception and biological aspects.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The information intercepted by the passage of sound waves through the ear is understood and interpreted through the brain, emphasizing the connection between the mind and acoustics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Psychological changes have been seen as brain waves slow down or speed up as a result of varying auditory stimulus which can in turn affect the way one thinks, feels, or even behaves.
[src:momentum/acoustics] This correlation can be viewed in normal, everyday situations in which listening to an upbeat or uptempo song can cause one's foot to start tapping or a slower song can leave one feeling calm and serene.
[src:momentum/acoustics] In a deeper biological look at the phenomenon of psychoacoustics, it was discovered that the central nervous system is activated by basic acoustical characteristics of music.
[src:momentum/acoustics] By observing how the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spine, is influenced by acoustics, the pathway in which acoustics affects the mind, and essentially the body, is evident.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Acousticians study the production, processing and perception of speech.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Speech recognition and speech synthesis are two important areas of speech processing using computers.
[src:momentum/acoustics] The subject also overlaps with the disciplines of physics, physiology, psychology, and linguistics.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Structural acoustics is the study of motions and interactions of mechanical systems with their environments and the methods of their measurement, analysis, and control.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Ultrasonics deals with sounds at frequencies too high to be heard by humans.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Specialisms include medical ultrasonics (including medical ultrasonography), ultrasonic sensors, sonochemistry, ultrasonic testing, material characterisation and underwater acoustics (sonar).
[src:momentum/acoustics] Underwater acoustics is the scientific study of natural and man-made sounds underwater.
[src:momentum/acoustics] Applications include sonar to locate submarines, underwater communication by whales, climate change monitoring by measuring sea temperatures acoustically, sonic weapons, and marine bioacoustics.
[src:momentum/momentum] In Newtonian mechanics, **momentum** (pl.: **momenta** or **momentums**; more specifically **linear momentum** or **translational momentum**) is the product of the mass and velocity of an object.
[src:momentum/momentum] It is a vector quantity, possessing a magnitude and a direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] Newton's second law of motion states that the rate of change of a body's momentum is equal to the net force acting on it.
[src:momentum/momentum] Momentum depends on the frame of reference, but in any inertial frame of reference, it is a *conserved* quantity, meaning that if a closed system is not affected by external forces, its total momentum does not change.
[src:momentum/momentum] Momentum is also conserved in special relativity (with a modified formula) and, in a modified form, in electrodynamics, quantum mechanics, quantum field theory, and general relativity.
[src:momentum/momentum] It is an expression of one of the fundamental symmetries of space and time: translational symmetry.
[src:momentum/momentum] Advanced formulations of classical mechanics, Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, allow one to choose coordinate systems that incorporate symmetries and constraints.
[src:momentum/momentum] In these systems the conserved quantity is **generalized momentum**, and in general this is different from the **kinetic** momentum defined above.
[src:momentum/momentum] The concept of generalized momentum is carried over into quantum mechanics, where it becomes an operator on a wave function.
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum and position operators are related by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:momentum/momentum] In continuous systems such as electromagnetic fields, fluid dynamics and deformable bodies, a **momentum density** can be defined as momentum per volume (a volume-specific quantity) and is said to satisfy a conservation law.
[src:momentum/momentum] A continuum version of the conservation of momentum leads to equations such as the Navier–Stokes equations for fluids or the Cauchy momentum equation for deformable solids or fluids.
[src:momentum/momentum] Momentum is a vector quantity: it has both magnitude and direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] Since momentum has a direction, it can be used to predict the resulting direction and speed of motion of objects after they collide.
[src:momentum/momentum] Below, the basic properties of momentum are described in one dimension.
[src:momentum/momentum] The vector equations are almost identical to the scalar equations (see multiple dimensions).
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum of a particle is conventionally represented by the letter *p*.
[src:momentum/momentum] The unit of momentum is the product of the units of mass and velocity.
[src:momentum/momentum] In SI units, if the mass is in kilograms and the velocity is in meters per second then the momentum is in kilogram meters per second (kg⋅m/s).
[src:momentum/momentum] In cgs units, if the mass is in grams and the velocity in centimeters per second, then the momentum is in gram centimeters per second (g⋅cm/s).
[src:momentum/momentum] Being a vector, momentum has magnitude and direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, a 1 kg model airplane, traveling due north at 1 m/s in straight and level flight, has a momentum of 1 kg⋅m/s due north measured with reference to the ground.
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum of a system of particles is the vector sum of their momenta.
[src:momentum/momentum] If one or more of the particles is moving, the center of mass of the system will generally be moving as well (unless the system is in pure rotation around it).
[src:momentum/momentum] hence the net force is equal to the mass of the particle times its acceleration.
[src:momentum/momentum] In a closed system (one that does not exchange any matter with its surroundings and is not acted on by external forces) the total momentum remains constant.
[src:momentum/momentum] This fact, known as the **law of conservation of momentum**, is implied by Newton's laws of motion.
[src:momentum/momentum] Suppose, for example, that two particles interact.
[src:momentum/momentum] As explained by the third law, the forces between them are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] If the particles are numbered 1 and 2, the second law states that *F*1 = ⁠d*p*1/d*t*⁠ and *F*2 = ⁠d*p*2/d*t*⁠.
[src:momentum/momentum] This law holds no matter how complicated the force is between particles.
[src:momentum/momentum] Similarly, if there are several particles, the momentum exchanged between each pair of particles adds to zero, so the total change in momentum is zero.
[src:momentum/momentum] This conservation law applies to all interactions, including collisions (both elastic and inelastic) and separations caused by explosive forces.
[src:momentum/momentum] It can also be generalized to situations where Newton's laws do not hold, such as in relativistic situations and those involving electrodynamics.
[src:momentum/momentum] Momentum is a measurable quantity, and the measurement depends on the frame of reference.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, if an aircraft of mass 1,000 kg flies through the air at a speed of 50 m/s, its momentum is 50,000 kg · m/s, but if the aircraft flies into a headwind of 5 m/s, its speed relative to the Earth's surface is only 45 m/s and its momentum drops to 45,000 kg · m/s.
[src:momentum/momentum] In both frames of reference, any change in momentum will be found to be consistent with the relevant laws of physics.
[src:momentum/momentum] Suppose x is a position in an inertial frame of reference.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is called a Galilean transformation.
[src:momentum/momentum] Thus, momentum is conserved in both reference frames.
[src:momentum/momentum] Moreover, as long as the force has the same form, in both frames, Newton's second law is unchanged.
[src:momentum/momentum] Forces such as Newtonian gravity, which depend only on the scalar distance between objects, satisfy this criterion.
[src:momentum/momentum] This independence of reference frame is called Newtonian relativity or Galilean invariance.
[src:momentum/momentum] A change of reference frame can often simplify calculations of motion.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, in a collision of two particles, a reference frame can be chosen where one particle begins at rest.
[src:momentum/momentum] Another commonly used reference frame is the center of mass frame – one that is moving with the center of mass.
[src:momentum/momentum] In this frame, the total momentum is zero.
[src:momentum/momentum] If two particles, each of known momentum, collide and coalesce, the law of conservation of momentum can be used to determine the momentum of the coalesced body.
[src:momentum/momentum] If the outcome of the collision is that the two particles separate, the law is not sufficient to determine the momentum of each particle.
[src:momentum/momentum] If the momentum of one particle after the collision is known, the law can be used to determine the momentum of the other particle.
[src:momentum/momentum] Alternatively if the combined kinetic energy after the collision is known, the law can be used to determine the momentum of each particle after the collision.
[src:momentum/momentum] Kinetic energy is usually not conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] If it is conserved, the collision is called an *elastic collision*; if not, it is an *inelastic collision*.
[src:momentum/momentum] An elastic collision is one in which no kinetic energy is transformed into heat or some other form of energy.
[src:momentum/momentum] Perfectly elastic collisions can occur when the objects do not touch each other, as for example in atomic or nuclear scattering where electric repulsion keeps the objects apart.
[src:momentum/momentum] A slingshot maneuver of a satellite around a planet can also be viewed as a perfectly elastic collision.
[src:momentum/momentum] A collision between two pool balls is a good example of an *almost* totally elastic collision, due to their high rigidity, but when bodies come in contact there is always some dissipation.
[src:momentum/momentum] A head-on elastic collision between two bodies can be represented by velocities in one dimension, along a line passing through the bodies.
[src:momentum/momentum] A change of reference frame can simplify analysis of a collision.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, suppose there are two bodies of equal mass m, one stationary and one approaching the other at a speed v (as in the figure).
[src:momentum/momentum] The center of mass is moving at speed ⁠*v*/2⁠ and both bodies are moving towards it at speed ⁠*v*/2⁠.
[src:momentum/momentum] Because of the symmetry, after the collision both must be moving away from the center of mass at the same speed.
[src:momentum/momentum] Adding the speed of the center of mass to both, we find that the body that was moving is now stopped and the other is moving away at speed v.
[src:momentum/momentum] The bodies have exchanged their velocities.
[src:momentum/momentum] Regardless of the velocities of the bodies, a switch to the center of mass frame leads us to the same conclusion.
[src:momentum/momentum] If one body has much greater mass than the other, its velocity will be little affected by a collision while the other body will experience a large change.
[src:momentum/momentum] In an inelastic collision, some of the kinetic energy of the colliding bodies is converted into other forms of energy (such as heat or sound).
[src:momentum/momentum] In a perfectly inelastic collision (such as a bug hitting a windshield), both bodies have the same motion afterwards.
[src:momentum/momentum] A head-on inelastic collision between two bodies can be represented by velocities in one dimension, along a line passing through the bodies.
[src:momentum/momentum] If the velocities are *v*A1 and *v*B1 before the collision then in a perfectly inelastic collision both bodies will be travelling with velocity v2 after the collision.
[src:momentum/momentum] In a different situation, if the frame of reference is moving at the final velocity such that $v_{2}=0$ , the objects would be brought to rest by a perfectly inelastic collision and 100% of the kinetic energy is converted to other forms of energy.
[src:momentum/momentum] In this instance the initial velocities of the bodies would be non-zero, or the bodies would have to be massless.
[src:momentum/momentum] One measure of the inelasticity of the collision is the coefficient of restitution *C*R, defined as the ratio of relative velocity of separation to relative velocity of approach.
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum and energy equations also apply to the motions of objects that begin together and then move apart.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, an explosion is the result of a chain reaction that transforms potential energy stored in chemical, mechanical, or nuclear form into kinetic energy, acoustic energy, and electromagnetic radiation.
[src:momentum/momentum] Rockets also make use of conservation of momentum: propellant is thrust outward, gaining momentum, and an equal and opposite momentum is imparted to the rocket.
[src:momentum/momentum] Real motion has both direction and velocity and must be represented by a vector.
[src:momentum/momentum] In a coordinate system with *x*, *y*, *z* axes, velocity has components *v**x* in the x-direction, *v**y* in the y-direction, *v**z* in the z-direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] The equations in the previous sections, work in vector form if the scalars p and v are replaced by vectors **p** and **v**.
[src:momentum/momentum] Each vector equation represents three scalar equations.
[src:momentum/momentum] The kinetic energy equations are exceptions to the above replacement rule.
[src:momentum/momentum] Often coordinates can be chosen so that only two components are needed, as in the figure.
[src:momentum/momentum] Each component can be obtained separately and the results combined to produce a vector result.
[src:momentum/momentum] A simple construction involving the center of mass frame can be used to show that if a stationary elastic sphere is struck by a moving sphere, the two will head off at right angles after the collision (as in the figure).
[src:momentum/momentum] The concept of momentum plays a fundamental role in explaining the behavior of variable-mass objects such as a rocket ejecting fuel or a star accreting gas.
[src:momentum/momentum] In analyzing such an object, one treats the object's mass as a function that varies with time: *m*(*t*).
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum of the object at time t is therefore *p*(*t*) = *m*(*t*)*v*(*t*).
[src:momentum/momentum] This equation does not correctly describe the motion of variable-mass objects.
[src:momentum/momentum] where u is the velocity of the ejected/accreted mass *as seen in the object's rest frame*.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is distinct from v, which is the velocity of the object itself as seen in an inertial frame.
[src:momentum/momentum] This equation is derived by keeping track of both the momentum of the object as well as the momentum of the ejected/accreted mass (d*m*).
[src:momentum/momentum] When considered together, the object and the mass (d*m*) constitute a closed system in which total momentum is conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] Newton's laws can be difficult to apply to many kinds of motion because the motion is limited by *constraints*.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, a bead on an abacus is constrained to move along its wire and a pendulum bob is constrained to swing at a fixed distance from the pivot.
[src:momentum/momentum] Many such constraints can be incorporated by changing the normal Cartesian coordinates to a set of *generalized coordinates* that may be fewer in number.
[src:momentum/momentum] Refined mathematical methods have been developed for solving mechanics problems in generalized coordinates.
[src:momentum/momentum] They introduce a *generalized momentum*, also known as the *canonical momentum* or *conjugate momentum*, that extends the concepts of both linear momentum and angular momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] To distinguish it from generalized momentum, the product of mass and velocity is also referred to as *mechanical momentum*, *kinetic momentum* or *kinematic momentum*.
[src:momentum/momentum] The two main methods are described below.
[src:momentum/momentum] If a coordinate *q**i* is not a Cartesian coordinate, the associated generalized momentum component *p**i* does not necessarily have the dimensions of linear momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] Even if *q**i* is a Cartesian coordinate, *p**i* will not be the same as the mechanical momentum if the potential depends on velocity.
[src:momentum/momentum] Some sources represent the kinematic momentum by the symbol **Π**.
[src:momentum/momentum] In this mathematical framework, a generalized momentum is associated with the generalized coordinates.
[src:momentum/momentum] Each component *p**j* is said to be the *conjugate momentum* for the coordinate *q**j*.
[src:momentum/momentum] Now if a given coordinate *q**i* does not appear in the Lagrangian (although its time derivative might appear), then *p**j* is constant.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is the generalization of the conservation of momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] Even if the generalized coordinates are just the ordinary spatial coordinates, the conjugate momenta are not necessarily the ordinary momentum coordinates.
[src:momentum/momentum] An example is found in the section on electromagnetism.
[src:momentum/momentum] In Hamiltonian mechanics, the Lagrangian (a function of generalized coordinates and their derivatives) is replaced by a Hamiltonian that is a function of generalized coordinates and momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] where the momentum is obtained by differentiating the Lagrangian as above.
[src:momentum/momentum] As in Lagrangian mechanics, if a generalized coordinate does not appear in the Hamiltonian, its conjugate momentum component is conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] Conservation of momentum is a mathematical consequence of the homogeneity (shift symmetry) of space (position in space is the canonical conjugate quantity to momentum).
[src:momentum/momentum] That is, conservation of momentum is a consequence of the fact that the laws of physics do not depend on position; this is a special case of Noether's theorem.
[src:momentum/momentum] For systems that do not have this symmetry, it may not be possible to define conservation of momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] Examples where conservation of momentum does not apply include curved spacetimes in general relativity or time crystals in condensed matter physics.
[src:momentum/momentum] In fields such as fluid dynamics and solid mechanics, it is not feasible to follow the motion of individual atoms or molecules.
[src:momentum/momentum] Instead, the materials must be approximated by a continuum in which, at each point, there is a particle or fluid parcel that is assigned the average of the properties of atoms in a small region nearby.
[src:momentum/momentum] In particular, it has a density ρ and velocity **v** that depend on time t and position **r**.
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum per unit volume is *ρ***v**.
[src:momentum/momentum] Consider a column of water in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:momentum/momentum] All the forces on the water are in balance and the water is motionless.
[src:momentum/momentum] On any given drop of water, two forces are balanced.
[src:momentum/momentum] The first is gravity, which acts directly on each atom and molecule inside.
[src:momentum/momentum] The gravitational force per unit volume is *ρ***g**, where **g** is the gravitational acceleration.
[src:momentum/momentum] The second force is the sum of all the forces exerted on its surface by the surrounding water.
[src:momentum/momentum] The force from below is greater than the force from above by just the amount needed to balance gravity.
[src:momentum/momentum] The normal force per unit area is the pressure p.
[src:momentum/momentum] If the forces are not balanced, the droplet accelerates.
[src:momentum/momentum] This acceleration is not simply the partial derivative ⁠*∂***v**/*∂**t*⁠ because the fluid in a given volume changes with time.
[src:momentum/momentum] Applied to any physical quantity, the material derivative includes the rate of change at a point and the changes due to advection as fluid is carried past the point.
[src:momentum/momentum] Per unit volume, the rate of change in momentum is equal to *ρ*⁠*D***v**/*D**t*⁠.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is equal to the net force on the droplet.
[src:momentum/momentum] Forces that can change the momentum of a droplet include the gradient of the pressure and gravity, as above.
[src:momentum/momentum] In addition, surface forces can deform the droplet.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the simplest case, a shear stress τ, exerted by a force parallel to the surface of the droplet, is proportional to the rate of deformation or strain rate.
[src:momentum/momentum] Such a shear stress occurs if the fluid has a velocity gradient because the fluid is moving faster on one side than another.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is also a flux, or flow per unit area, of x-momentum through the surface.
[src:momentum/momentum] These are known as the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:momentum/momentum] The momentum balance equations can be extended to more general materials, including solids.
[src:momentum/momentum] For each surface with normal in direction i and force in direction j, there is a stress component *σ**i**j*.
[src:momentum/momentum] The nine components make up the Cauchy stress tensor **σ**, which includes both pressure and shear.
[src:momentum/momentum] The Cauchy momentum equation is broadly applicable to deformations of solids and liquids.
[src:momentum/momentum] The relationship between the stresses and the strain rate depends on the properties of the material (see Types of viscosity).
[src:momentum/momentum] A disturbance in a medium gives rise to oscillations, or waves, that propagate away from their source.
[src:momentum/momentum] In a solid, similar equations can be obtained for propagation of pressure (P-waves) and shear (S-waves).
[src:momentum/momentum] The flux, or transport per unit area, of a momentum component *ρ**v**j* by a velocity *v**i* is equal to *ρ**v**j**v**j*.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the linear approximation that leads to the above acoustic equation, the time average of this flux is zero.
[src:momentum/momentum] However, nonlinear effects can give rise to a nonzero average.
[src:momentum/momentum] It is possible for momentum flux to occur even though the wave itself does not have a mean momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] In Maxwell's equations, the forces between particles are mediated by electric and magnetic fields.
[src:momentum/momentum] It has an electric potential *φ*(**r**, *t*) and magnetic vector potential **A**(**r**, *t*).
[src:momentum/momentum] The quantity *V* = *q***A** is sometimes called the *potential momentum*.
[src:momentum/momentum] It is the momentum due to the interaction of the particle with the electromagnetic fields.
[src:momentum/momentum] The name is an analogy with the potential energy *U* = *q**φ*, which is the energy due to the interaction of the particle with the electromagnetic fields.
[src:momentum/momentum] These quantities form a four-vector, so the analogy is consistent; besides, the concept of potential momentum is important in explaining the so-called hidden momentum of the electromagnetic fields.
[src:momentum/momentum] In Newtonian mechanics, the law of conservation of momentum can be derived from the law of action and reaction, which states that every force has a reciprocating equal and opposite force.
[src:momentum/momentum] Under some circumstances, moving charged particles can exert forces on each other in non-opposite directions.
[src:momentum/momentum] Nevertheless, the combined momentum of the particles and the electromagnetic field is conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] The Lorentz force imparts a momentum to the particle, so by Newton's second law the particle must impart a momentum to the electromagnetic fields.
[src:momentum/momentum] where *μ*0 is the vacuum permeability and c is the speed of light.
[src:momentum/momentum] If momentum is to be conserved over the volume V over a region Q, changes in the momentum of matter through the Lorentz force must be balanced by changes in the momentum of the electromagnetic field and outflow of momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] The term on the right is an integral over the surface area Σ of the surface σ representing momentum flow into and out of the volume, and *n*j is a component of the surface normal of S.
[src:momentum/momentum] The above results are for the *microscopic* Maxwell equations, applicable to electromagnetic forces in a vacuum (or on a very small scale in media).
[src:momentum/momentum] It is more difficult to define momentum density in media because the division into electromagnetic and mechanical is arbitrary.
[src:momentum/momentum] The electromagnetic stress tensor depends on the properties of the media.
[src:momentum/momentum] In quantum mechanics, momentum is defined as a self-adjoint operator on the wave function.
[src:momentum/momentum] The Heisenberg uncertainty principle defines limits on how accurately the momentum and position of a single observable system can be known at once.
[src:momentum/momentum] In quantum mechanics, position and momentum are conjugate variables.
[src:momentum/momentum] where ∇ is the gradient operator, ħ is the reduced Planck constant, and i is the imaginary unit.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is a commonly encountered form of the momentum operator, though the momentum operator in other bases can take other forms.
[src:momentum/momentum] where the operator **p** acting on a wave eigenfunction *ψ*(*p*) yields that wave function multiplied by the eigenvalue p, in an analogous fashion to the way that the position operator acting on a wave function *ψ*(*x*) yields that wave function multiplied by the eigenvalue x.
[src:momentum/momentum] Electromagnetic radiation (including visible light, ultraviolet light, and radio waves) is carried by photons.
[src:momentum/momentum] Even though photons (the particle aspect of light) have no mass, they still carry momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] This leads to applications such as the solar sail.
[src:momentum/momentum] The calculation of the momentum of light within dielectric media is somewhat controversial (see Abraham–Minkowski controversy).
[src:momentum/momentum] Newtonian physics assumes that absolute time and space exist outside of any observer; this gives rise to Galilean invariance.
[src:momentum/momentum] It also results in a prediction that the speed of light can vary from one reference frame to another.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is contrary to what has been observed.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the special theory of relativity, Einstein keeps the postulate that the equations of motion do not depend on the reference frame, but assumes that the speed of light c is invariant.
[src:momentum/momentum] As a result, position and time in two reference frames are related by the Lorentz transformation instead of the Galilean transformation.
[src:momentum/momentum] Consider, for example, one reference frame moving relative to another at velocity v in the x direction.
[src:momentum/momentum] Newton's second law, with mass fixed, is not invariant under a Lorentz transformation.
[src:momentum/momentum] Within the domain of classical mechanics, relativistic momentum closely approximates Newtonian momentum: at low velocity, *γ**m*0**v** is approximately equal to *m*0**v**, the Newtonian expression for momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the theory of special relativity, physical quantities are expressed in terms of four-vectors that include time as a fourth coordinate along with the three space coordinates.
[src:momentum/momentum] These vectors are generally represented by capital letters, for example **R** for position.
[src:momentum/momentum] The expression for the *four-momentum* depends on how the coordinates are expressed.
[src:momentum/momentum] Time may be given in its normal units or multiplied by the speed of light so that all the components of the four-vector have dimensions of length.
[src:momentum/momentum] is invariant under Lorentz transformations (in this expression and in what follows the (+ − − −) metric signature has been used, different authors use different conventions).
[src:momentum/momentum] Mathematically this invariance can be ensured in one of two ways: by treating the four-vectors as Euclidean vectors and multiplying time by √−1; or by keeping time a real quantity and embedding the vectors in a Minkowski space.
[src:momentum/momentum] Thus, conservation of four-momentum is Lorentz-invariant and implies conservation of both mass and energy.
[src:momentum/momentum] and is invariant across all reference frames.
[src:momentum/momentum] In a game of relativistic "billiards", if a stationary particle is hit by a moving particle in an elastic collision, the paths formed by the two afterwards will form an acute angle.
[src:momentum/momentum] This is unlike the non-relativistic case where they travel at right angles.
[src:momentum/momentum] For a particle, the relationship between temporal components, *E* = *ħ**ω*, is the Planck–Einstein relation, and the relation between spatial components, **p** = *ħ***k**, describes a de Broglie matter wave.
[src:momentum/momentum] In about 530 AD, John Philoponus developed a concept of momentum in *On Physics*, a commentary to Aristotle's *Physics*.
[src:momentum/momentum] Aristotle claimed that everything that is moving must be kept moving by something.
[src:momentum/momentum] For example, a thrown ball must be kept moving by motions of the air.
[src:momentum/momentum] Philoponus pointed out the absurdity in Aristotle's claim that motion of an object is promoted by the same air that is resisting its passage.
[src:momentum/momentum] He proposed instead that an impetus was imparted to the object in the act of throwing it.
[src:momentum/momentum] In 1020, Ibn Sīnā (also known by his Latinized name Avicenna) read Philoponus and published his own theory of motion in *The Book of Healing*.
[src:momentum/momentum] He agreed that an impetus is imparted to a projectile by the thrower; but unlike Philoponus, who believed that it was a temporary virtue that would decline even in a vacuum, he viewed it as a persistent, requiring external forces such as air resistance to dissipate it.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the 13th and 14th century, Peter Olivi and Jean Buridan read and refined the work of Philoponus, and possibly that of Ibn Sīnā.
[src:momentum/momentum] Buridan, who in about 1350 was made rector of the University of Paris, referred to impetus being proportional to the weight times the speed.
[src:momentum/momentum] Moreover, Buridan's theory was different from his predecessor's in that he did not consider impetus to be self-dissipating, asserting that a body would be arrested by the forces of air resistance and gravity which might be opposing its impetus.
[src:momentum/momentum] In *Principles of Philosophy* (*Principia Philosophiae*) from 1644, the French philosopher René Descartes defined "quantity of motion" (*Latin: quantitas motus*) as the product of size and speed, and claimed that the total quantity of motion in the universe is conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] This should not be read as a statement of the modern law of conservation of momentum, since Descartes had no concept of mass as distinct from weight and size.
[src:momentum/momentum] (The concept of mass, as distinct from weight, was introduced by Newton in 1686.) More important, he believed that it is speed rather than velocity that is conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] So for Descartes, if a moving object were to bounce off a surface, changing its direction but not its speed, there would be no change in its quantity of motion.
[src:momentum/momentum] Galileo, in his *Two New Sciences* (published in 1638), used the Italian word *impeto* to similarly describe Descartes's quantity of motion.
[src:momentum/momentum] In the 1600s, Christiaan Huygens concluded quite early that Descartes's laws for the elastic collision of two bodies must be wrong, and he formulated the correct laws.
[src:momentum/momentum] An important step was his recognition of the Galilean invariance of the problems.
[src:momentum/momentum] His views then took many years to be circulated.
[src:momentum/momentum] He passed them on in person to William Brouncker and Christopher Wren in London, in 1661.
[src:momentum/momentum] What Spinoza wrote to Henry Oldenburg about them, in 1666 during the Second Anglo-Dutch War, was guarded.
[src:momentum/momentum] Huygens had actually worked them out in a manuscript *De motu corporum ex percussione* in the period 1652–1656.
[src:momentum/momentum] The war ended in 1667, and Huygens announced his results to the Royal Society in 1668.
[src:momentum/momentum] He published them in the *Journal des sçavans* in 1669.
[src:momentum/momentum] In 1670, John Wallis, in *Mechanica sive De Motu, Tractatus Geometricus*, stated the law of conservation of momentum: "the initial state of the body, either of rest or of motion, will persist" and "If the force is greater than the resistance, motion will result".
[src:momentum/momentum] Wallis used *momentum* for quantity of motion, and *vis* for force.
[src:momentum/momentum] In 1686, Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, in *Discourse on Metaphysics*, gave an argument against Descartes' construction of the conservation of the "quantity of motion" using an example of dropping blocks of different sizes different distances.
[src:momentum/momentum] He points out that force is conserved but quantity of motion, construed as the product of size and speed of an object, is not conserved.
[src:momentum/momentum] In 1687, Isaac Newton, in *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, just like Wallis, showed a similar casting around for words to use for the mathematical momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] His Definition II defines *quantitas motus*, "quantity of motion", as "arising from the velocity and quantity of matter conjointly", which identifies it as momentum.
[src:momentum/momentum] Thus when in Law II he refers to *mutatio motus*, "change of motion", being proportional to the force impressed, he is generally taken to mean momentum and not motion.
[src:momentum/momentum] In 1721, John Jennings published *Miscellanea*, where the momentum in its current mathematical sense is attested, five years before the final edition of Newton's *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:momentum/momentum] *Momentum* M or "quantity of motion" was being defined for students as "a rectangle", the product of Q and V, where Q is "quantity of material" and V is "velocity", ⁠*s*/*t*⁠.
